Package: xtables-addons-asn
Architecture: linux-any
Depends: ${shlibs:Depends},
         ${misc:Depends},
         iptables (>= 1.4.5),
         bgpdump,
         libtext-csv-xs-perl,
         libnet-ip-perl,
         libnet-netmask-perl,
         wget | curl
Recommends: cron | systemd-cron
Suggests: xtables-addons-asn-source
Description: IPTables ASN filtering module
 This package provides an iptables/netfilter kernel module for filtering
 network traffic based on Autonomous System Numbers (ASN). It enables
 efficient packet filtering by ASN, making it useful for geolocation-based
 filtering, traffic analysis, and network security applications.
 .
 Features:
  * Support for 4-byte ASN numbers
  * IPv4 and IPv6 support
  * High-performance binary search for IP range matching
  * Real-time BGP data processing from RouteViews.org
  * Native netfilter integration with minimal overhead

Package: xtables-addons-asn-source
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
         module-assistant,
         debhelper,
         build-essential,
         linux-headers-generic | linux-headers
Description: Source for the xtables-addons-asn kernel module
 This package provides the source code for the xtables-addons-asn kernel
 module. It can be used with module-assistant or DKMS to build the kernel
 module for custom kernels.
 .
 This package is useful for users who need to build the module against
 a kernel that doesn't have pre-built module packages available.

Package: xtables-addons-asn-dkms
Architecture: all
Depends: ${misc:Depends},
         dkms,
         linux-headers-generic | linux-headers
Conflicts: xtables-addons-asn-source
Description: DKMS source for the xtables-addons-asn kernel module
 This package provides the xtables-addons-asn kernel module in a form
 suitable for use with DKMS (Dynamic Kernel Module Support). DKMS will
 automatically build and install the module whenever a new kernel is
 installed, ensuring compatibility across kernel updates.
 .
 This is the recommended package for users who frequently update their
 kernel or use custom kernels.
